04768nam a22005655i 9780822390671DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19991999ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223906717 a10.1515/97808223906712doi  a(DE-B1597)554351  a(OCoLC)1229161135  a(OCoLC)1226680178  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aJC311b.C615 1999 7aPOL0100002bisacsh1 aCohen, Shari J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPolitics without a Past :bThe Absence of History in Postcommunist Nationalism /cShari J. Cohen. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1999] 4cÂ©1999  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 ae-Duke books scholarly collection00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tChronology -- t1: The Legacy of Two Totalitarianisms -- t2: Historical Consciousness, Family Stories, and Nationalism -- t3: Weak Nationalism in Slovakia: The Precommunist Period -- t4: Islands of History: The Democrats and Nationalists -- t5: Organized Forgetting: Elites with No History -- t6: Nationalism without Nationalists? Democracy without Democrats? -- t7: Politics in a Hall of Mirrors -- t8: Conclusion -- tAppendix: List of Interviews -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Politics without a Past Shari J. Cohen offers a powerful challenge tocommon characterizations of postcommunist politics as either a resurgence ofaggressive nationalism or an evolution toward Western-style democracy. Cohendraws upon extensive field research to paint a picture of postcommunistpolitical life in which ideological labels are meaningless and exchangeableat will, political parties appear and disappear regularly, and citizensremain unengaged in the political process.In contrast to the conventional wisdom, which locates the roots of widespread intranational strife in deeply rooted national identities from the past, Cohen argues that a profound ideological vacuum has fueled destructive tension throughout postcommunist Europe and the former Soviet Union. She uses Slovakia as a case study to reveal that communist regimes bequeathed an insidious form of historical amnesia to the majority of the political elite and the societies they govern. Slovakia was particularly vulnerable to communist intervention since its precommunist national consciousness was so weak and its only period of statehood prior to 1993 was as a Nazi puppet-state. To demonstrate her argument, Cohen focuses on Slovakia's failure to forge a collective memory of the World War II experience. She shows how communist socialization prevented Slovaks from tying their individual family stories-of the Jewish deportations, of the anti-Nazi resistance, or of serving in the wartime government-to a larger historical narrative shared with others, leaving them bereft of historical or moral bearings.Politics without a Past develops an analytical framework that will be important for future research in Eastern Europe, the former Soviet Union, and beyond. Scholars in political science, history, East European and post-Soviet studies will find Cohen's methodology and conclusions enlightening. For policymakers, diplomats, and journalists who deal with the region, she offers valuable insights into the elusive nature of postcommunist societies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aHistoryxPhilosophy. 0aNationalism. 0aPost-communism. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822390671zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978082